lungs at maximal inspiration","Volume of air remaining after normal expiration"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVolume of air in lungs at maximal inspiration\u003C/strong\u003E correctly defines total lung capacity (TLC). TLC is approximately 6 L in healthy adults and represents the absolute maximum volume of air that the lungs can hold.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVolume of air that can be forcefully expired\u003C/strong\u003E describes vital capacity, which is the maximum volume that can be exhaled after a maximal inspiration. \u003Cstrong\u003EVolume of air remaining after normal expiration\u003C/strong\u003E describes functional residual capacity, the volume remaining in the lungs after passive expiration. \u003Cstrong\u003EVolume of air exchanged during normal breathing\u003C/strong\u003E describes tidal volume, typically around 500 mL during quiet breathing. \u003Cstrong\u003EVolume of air remaining after maximal expiration\u003C/strong\u003E describes residual volume, the volume that cannot be expelled even with maximal effort.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal lung capacity equals vital capacity plus residual volume. It is an important parameter that helps distinguish between restrictive lung diseases (where TLC is reduced) and obstructive lung diseases (where TLC is normal or increased).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Total lung capacity is the volume of air in the lungs at maximal inspiration, typically 6 L in healthy adults.","Total lung capacity equals vital capacity plus residual volume.","Total lung capacity is reduced in restrictive lung diseases and normal or increased in obstructive lung diseases."],"references":["West JB, Luks AM. West\u2019s respiratory physiology: the essentials. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Wolters Kluwer; 2015. Chapter 2; pg. 16.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96563"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18025"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96563"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T15:49:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T15:49:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10739"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114562"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4927"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:14:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type